<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900413-0061</DOCNO><DOCID>900413-0061.</DOCID><HL>   Justice Department Urged   To Monitor Meat Packers   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>04/13/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   The attorneys general of five Midwestern states urged theU.S. Justice Department to step up antitrust enforcement inthe meatpacking industry.   In a letter sent yesterday to U.S. Attorney General DickThornburgh, the state prosecutors cited statistics that theyclaim indicate dangerously high concentration of market sharein the meatpacking industry. For example, the state attorneysgeneral said that the four largest competitors in thebeefpacking industry control about 70% of the fed-cattlemarket, up from 39% in 1980.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;For the past decade, antitrust has been the forgottenarea of federal law enforcement,&quot; Minnesota's attorneygeneral, Hubert Humphrey III, said in a statementaccompanying release of the letter. Mr. Humphrey signed theletter along with his counterparts from Iowa, Montana, NorthDakota and South Dakota.   A Justice Department spokesman said Mr. Thornburgh hadn'tseen the letter, but that federal prosecutors have &quot;looked atthe meatpacking industry because of the concerns of meatproducers about concentration in that market.&quot; Thedepartment's &quot;antitrust division is aware of the situationand will continue to monitor it,&quot; the spokesman added.</TEXT></DOC>